00:01.780 --> 00:12.080
In 1987, the International Space University was founded to develop and implement
international space-related curriculum. This university would identify,

00:12.480 --> 00:21.800
assemble, and educate a new generation of young leaders from around the world.
By uniting these students in an intensive program of study and research, ISU

00:21.800 --> 00:29.960
would foster long-lasting ties between these future heads of industry,
government, and academia, creating an international network which would help

00:29.960 --> 00:42.660
assure cooperation in the opening of space. In the summer of 1988, that mission
was accomplished and the International Space University was born. For the first

00:42.660 --> 00:52.080
summer session of the International Space University, 104 of the world's top
graduate level students from 21 nations came together on the campus of the

00:52.080 --> 01:01.560
Massachusetts Institute of Technology. Having undergone a rigorous selection
program, these students participated in an experience that would change their

01:01.560 --> 01:12.120
lives and quite possibly the world forever. So what we are going to talk about
and what you are going to listen to and what you are going to take part in in

01:12.120 --> 01:25.360
the next 10 weeks is much more important than just a learning experience. It is
a creative experience. You are creating your future. There is nothing more

01:25.360 --> 01:37.640
important because in your future lies the history and the future of the human
species. The ISU class of 88 is going to be a major component in the space

01:37.640 --> 01:49.040
leadership of the world in the future. These are impressive young professionals
with a formidable list of credentials to their credit. They are gifted with

01:49.040 --> 01:59.000
enormous intelligence and unbelievable resources of energy. For over 60 days and
nights these students were immersed in one of the most rigorous and intensive

01:59.000 --> 02:09.500
space education programs ever organized. From the world's space powers to those
nations only now on the threshold of utilizing space technology, ISU has

02:09.500 --> 02:19.420
something to offer everyone. The whole process involves, or the training
involves, a look at all communication technologies and using satellites for

02:19.420 --> 02:31.060
remote sensing, monitoring the growth of forests or the spread of forests all
over the place, and, in my country, this is one of the technologies we require,

02:31.280 --> 02:43.240
and we'll use this to implement these facilities. I had a few ideas about space
and what does space means, but when I came here to ISU, and after the completion

02:43.240 --> 02:55.800
of this program, two-month intensive program, I can say that I learned a lot
during this program. Including 240 hours of lectures and instruction by leading

02:55.800 --> 03:06.960
experts from 14 nations, students are exposed to the latest ideas in all fields
of space development, exploration, technology, and administration. Stressing a

03:06.960 --> 03:15.960
multidisciplinary approach to education, ISU has developed courses in the
following eight departments of space studies. Architecture, business and

03:15.960 --> 03:27.840
management, engineering, life sciences, policy and law, resources and
manufacturing, satellite applications, physical sciences. The quality of the

03:27.840 --> 03:36.580
lectures we've had here has been just superb. We've had experts in space
business. For example, the Chief Designer of the Shuttle, Sy Rubenstein has

03:36.580 --> 03:45.500
come in. He is now President of Brockwell Space Transportation Systems, and he
has talked to us about what it means to be involved in space business. What

03:45.500 --> 03:55.940
better perspective could you have? We met the best in the field. I mean
professor wise and lecturer wise. And we saw insight or view that we never could

03:55.940 --> 04:06.500
see it from school or from anywhere else. Normally confined to one or two areas
of specialization, ISU students are taught the importance of broad-based

04:06.500 --> 04:16.320
knowledge, developing the skills necessary to effectively work in a multi
-disciplinary environment. To accomplish this goal, each session students work

04:16.320 --> 04:27.160
on a simulation of a major space project. During the 1988 session, they spent
over 280 hours working with interdisciplinary teams, which planned and designed

04:27.160 --> 04:39.680
a viable lunar base for research and industry. Hands-on experiments such as this
one are vital to giving students and faculty a feel for the real problems that

04:39.680 --> 04:49.140
are involved in space operations. And no student who has operated the system
will be able have any doubts about whether or not it's possible to control

04:49.140 --> 05:00.960
machinery in real time on the moon. The multidisciplinary approach that this
program took has been a real eye opener. ISU students represent a global network

05:00.960 --> 05:12.560
of expertise and talent, a benefit which is of extreme importance in this global
economy. What's important is experience of getting to know other people, getting

05:12.560 --> 05:23.080
a current base, you know the people when you have to talk to them in the future,
and everything's going to be so much easier when you can negotiate with friends

05:23.080 --> 05:36.200
than with people you've never met before. So it needs a lot of international
collaboration in the future to establish a space station or a lunar base. What I

05:36.200 --> 05:46.600
will go away with is a base of contacts all over the world, of people who are my
age or approximately my age who have my motivation are interested in the things

05:46.600 --> 05:58.740
that I'm interested in. And that is an incredible bomb to have. ISU is going to
be the training ground for those savvy individuals who know how to operate in

05:58.740 --> 06:11.760
this world marketplace and know how to cut across the boundaries of governments
and corporations to pull together projects and programs and make them work. ISU

06:11.760 --> 06:21.980
is looking to the future, and that future is bright. After four more summer
sessions hosted at the world's greatest educational institutions, ISU will open

06:21.980 --> 06:34.540
the doors on its first permanent campus during the International Space Year
1992. From this central campus, ISU will beam lectures and teleconferences to

06:34.540 --> 06:45.200
advance students and researchers at daughter campuses around the world. The goal
of ISU is to become the first true space university at the dawn of the 21st

06:45.200 --> 06:54.540
century with students and faculty actually studying and working in space. 
I think the ISU concept, as well as other concepts like this, is the

06:54.540 --> 07:04.960
absolute seedbed to spring new ideas in innovation into our total process. The
ISU is building international bridges. To move out into space is going to be

07:04.960 --> 07:12.820
very, very expensive. And I think if we're going to do it seriously, we are
going to have to do it as an international endeavour. I think the ISU

07:15.480 --> 07:23.360
plants the seeds of international cooperation and demonstrates the benefits to
its student body and that can only be to the good in the long run. Space is

07:23.360 --> 07:33.720
going to invade all the areas of our being in the next 20 or 30 years and it's
in everybody's interest to make sure that it's there, it's free, it's

07:33.720 --> 07:44.040
international and it's forward-looking. if I had any money, I would put it in.
Dozens of space organizations and sponsors have stepped forward to support the

07:44.040 --> 07:53.940
ISU dream of a new worldwide network of young leaders who have the capabilities
and drive to push their nations and companies into leading roles as we enter the

07:53.940 --> 08:06.120
21st century. These visionary sponsors see the International Space University as
the important investment that it is. By supporting an ISU student today, They

08:06.120 --> 08:17.100
are creating a leader for tomorrow. As the people of Earth take their first
steps outward into the solar system, we are faced with a choice. Do we do it

08:17.100 --> 08:28.700
alone or together? Will we carry on as we have for thousands of years, or do we
try something new? The students of the International Space University are ready

08:28.700 --> 08:37.520
to accept the challenge of tomorrow now. Together, we can reach the stars. 

