16:17.180 --> 16:27.720
Greetings to all you gathered for the first graduation ceremony of the
International Space University. I send especially warm wishes to my colleagues

16:27.720 --> 16:41.060
at MIT, my old friend Roy Gibson, and the men behind the ISU. Peter Diamandis,
Todd Hawley, Bob Richards and their colleagues. I'm particularly pleased that I

16:41.060 --> 16:49.980
can greet you while remaining comfortably at home on the other side of the
Earth. I never really expected the com sats would be so useful to me personally.

16:50.380 --> 17:02.080
In fact, I never expected to see them in my lifetime. You are the first
representatives of a true space-faring species whose world is not bounded by the

17:02.080 --> 17:17.460
confines of one planet. So let me share with you a passage I wrote back in 1969
for the history of the Apollo 11 mission, first on the moon. Half a billion

17:17.460 --> 17:29.980
years ago, the moon summoned life out of its first home, the sea, and led it
onto the empty land. For as it drew the tides across the barren continents of

17:29.980 --> 17:41.620
primeval Earth, their daily rhythm exposed to the sun and air the creatures of
the shadows. Most perished but some adapted to the new and hostile environment.

17:42.730 --> 17:53.680
The conquest of the land had begun. We shall never know when this happened on
the shores of what vanished sea. There were no eyes or cameras to record the

17:53.680 --> 18:08.820
event. Now the moon calls again and this time life responds with a roar that
shakes the sky. When a Saturn V soars spacewards on 4,000 tons of thrust, it

18:08.820 --> 18:20.840
signifies more than a trance of technology. It opens the next chapter of
evolution. Well, that was written in 1969. And we're going to return to the

18:20.840 --> 18:32.380
moon. But when we go there again, it will be in vehicles that will make the
Saturn V, for all its staggering complexity and its 150 million horsepower, look

18:32.380 --> 18:47.040
like a clumsy, inefficient dinosaur of the early space age. And this time, we
will stay. Space travel is a technological mutation that really should not have

18:47.040 --> 19:00.220
arrived until the 21st century. But thanks to the ambition and genius of men
like Wernher von Braun and Sergei Korolev and their influence upon such diverse

19:00.220 --> 19:13.500
individuals as Kennedy and Khrushchev, the moon was reached half a century ahead
of time. And now you can take advantage of this historical accident, for as Isaac

19:13.500 --> 19:26.420
Newton once remarked, you are standing on the shoulders of giants. The moon was
a fitting subject for our efforts during the first session of the ISU. Do not

19:26.420 --> 19:38.660
lose the momentum of your work, or the intensity of your vision, whatever
obstacles you may encounter. As H. G. Wells once put it, the choice is universe

19:38.660 --> 19:54.500
or nothing. The resources of that universe are, by all human standards,
infinite. There are no limits to growth among the stars. Unfortunately, there's

19:54.500 --> 20:06.300
a tragic mismatch between our present needs and our capabilities. The conquest
of space will not arrive soon enough to save millions from leading starved and

20:06.300 --> 20:18.640
stunted lives. Thus it is all the more urgent that we exploit to the utmost the
marvelous tools that space technology has already given us com sats,  Weather sats,

20:18.640 --> 20:31.680
geo sats, Earth resources sats, and all the other sats yet to be invented. this is
a reason as I've said many times in the past that the third world needs space

20:31.680 --> 20:35.620
technology even more urgently than the so-called developing world

20:39.060 --> 20:48.520
you will find in the years to come that the experience which you have shared
with your fellow ISU students will have changed your life to work with friends

20:48.520 --> 21:00.640
from a score of other nations will profoundly affect your world view and that
may well be the most important role of the ISU. As our terrestrial universities

21:00.640 --> 21:12.900
once first flourished during the times of great exploration and discovery on our
own planet so the ISU is a response to the first exploration of space. The

21:12.900 --> 21:26.560
blossoming of art and science during the Renaissance may now be repeated when
artists and poets join scientists and engineers at the new frontier as the

21:26.560 --> 21:36.940
university begins its second year in Europe and later in other locations around
the globe I eagerly await its growth to a permanent full-time institution which

21:36.940 --> 21:47.960
will train tomorrow's space professionals I would like to know the future that
you will help to create but that is a privilege to be reserved for your children

21:47.960 --> 22:03.140
and grandchildren it is they who to quote H.G. Wells again shall stand upon this
earth as one stands upon a footstool and reach yet their hand among the stars I

22:03.140 --> 22:14.280
wish you well for you represent a new evolutionary branch of humanity
Congratulations on your achievement and my very best wishes for your futures in

22:14.280 --> 22:16.640
space Thank you and goodbye.

